# Research basis for each measure

## Reaction time variability (intraindividual variability, IIV)
Hicks, K. et al. (2012). Intraindividual variability in reaction time is the strongest behavioral predictor of mild cognitive impairment. *Neuropsychology.*

## Critical Flicker Fusion (CFF)
Validated since the 1950s as a measure of CNS depression and sensory processing speed. Used to detect alcohol impairment, fatigue, and sedative drug effects. Still used as a sensitivity endpoint in dementia drug trials.

## Grip strength
Used clinically to track neurological decline in Parkinson's disease and post-stroke recovery. Grip asymmetry (dominant vs. non-dominant hand) is a particularly sensitive marker.

## Gait analysis
Hausdorff, J.M. et al. (2001). Gait variability and the risk of falls and cognitive decline. *Archives of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation.* Gait variability has been shown to predict Alzheimer's diagnosis up to 5 years before clinical symptoms.

## Stroop interference
Stroop, J.R. (1935). Studies of interference in serial verbal reactions. *Journal of Experimental Psychology.* One of the most widely used tests in clinical neuropsychology; sensitive to executive function decline in aging, ADHD, traumatic brain injury, and early dementia.

## Closest existing clinical tool
Cambridge Cognition's CANTAB platform — validated across 3,000+ published studies, used in pharmaceutical trials and research institutions. Apple partnered with Cambridge Cognition on a 23,000-participant study validating smartphone + wearable based cognitive assessment at scale — directionally supportive of CVMD's consumer thesis, though CANTAB itself is B2B/clinical, not a consumer product.
